                    { id: 2, text: 'Which of the following is an example of Secondary Data?', options: ['Conducting a live survey', 'Interviewing people on the street', 'Data extracted from a government census report', 'Measuring the heights of students in class'], correctAnswer: 2, explanation: 'Secondary data is data that has already been collected and published by someone else.' },
                    { id: 3, text: 'Which type of data is generally considered more reliable and accurate for a specific study?', options: ['Secondary Data', 'Primary Data', 'Tertiary Data', 'Internet Data'], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: 'Primary data is collected with the specific study in mind, making it highly reliable.' },
                    { id: 4, text: 'Data relating to qualitative attributes like gender, color, or honesty is called:', options: ['Quantitative Data', 'Discrete Data', 'Continuous Data', 'Qualitative Data'], correctAnswer: 3, explanation: 'Qualitative data describes categories or attributes that cannot be measured numerically.' },
                    { id: 5, text: 'Data that can be measured numerically (like height, weight, income) is called:', options: ['Qualitative Data', 'Quantitative Data', 'Nominal Data', 'Ordinal Data'], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: 'Quantitative data deals with numbers and things that can be measured objectively.' },
                    { id: 6, text: 'The number of students in a classroom is an example of a:', options: ['Continuous Variable', 'Discrete Variable', 'Qualitative Variable', 'Constant'], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: 'Discrete variables take on exact, countable whole numbers (you can\'t have 2.5 students).' },
                    { id: 7, text: 'The temperature of a city over a week is an example of a:', options: ['Continuous Variable', 'Discrete Variable', 'Qualitative Variable', 'Constant'], correctAnswer: 0, explanation: 'Continuous variables can take any fractional or decimal value within a range.' },
                    { id: 8, text: 'Unorganized data collected directly from an experiment before any grouping is known as:', options: ['Grouped data', 'Secondary data', 'Raw data', 'Frequency distribution'], correctAnswer: 2, explanation: 'Raw data is the initial, unprocessed data directly from the source.' },
                    { id: 9, text: 'Which method is NOT a way of collecting Primary Data?', options: ['Direct personal observation', 'Mailed questionnaires', 'Reading Wikipedia articles', 'Telephone interviews'], correctAnswer: 2, explanation: 'Reading Wikipedia is sourcing secondary data, not conducting primary research.' },
                    { id: 10, text: 'What is a "Questionnaire"?', options: ['A list of answers', 'A device to measure temperature', 'A structured list of questions used to gather primary data', 'A statistical formula'], correctAnswer: 2, explanation: 'A questionnaire is the most common tool for gathering primary data via surveys.' },
                    { id: 11, text: 'By definition, a "Project" is a:', options: ['Continuous daily routine', 'Temporary endeavor undertaken to create a unique product or service', 'Permanent organizational structure', 'Unplanned activity'], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: 'A project is defined by having a specific start and end date (temporary) and a unique outcome.' },
                    { id: 12, text: 'Which of the following is NOT an example of a project?', options: ['Building a new bridge', 'Developing a new software app', 'Daily maintenance of a school building', 'Planning a wedding'], correctAnswer: 2, explanation: 'Daily maintenance is a continuous, repetitive operation, not a temporary project.' },
                    { id: 13, text: 'What is the primary role of a Project Manager?', options: ['To fund the project', 'To execute all the technical work alone', 'To plan, execute, and close the project on time and within budget', 'To purchase materials only'], correctAnswer: 2, explanation: 'The PM leads the team to achieve project goals within the given constraints.' },
                    { id: 14, text: 'The "Triple Constraint" in project management refers to:', options: ['Time, Cost, and Scope', 'People, Process, and Tools', 'Planning, Execution, and Review', 'Quality, Risk, and Rewards'], correctAnswer: 0, explanation: 'If you change Time, Cost, or Scope, at least one of the other two must also change.' },
                    { id: 15, text: 'Who is a "Stakeholder" in a project?', options: ['Only the project manager', 'Only the people paying for the project', 'Anyone who is affected by or can affect the project', 'Only the government'], correctAnswer: 2, explanation: 'Stakeholders include the team, customers, sponsors, and even the local community.' },
                    { id: 16, text: 'What is the very first phase in a standard Project Life Cycle?', options: ['Planning', 'Execution', 'Closure', 'Initiation'], correctAnswer: 3, explanation: 'Initiation is where the project is defined at a high level and authorized.' },
                    { id: 17, text: '"Scope Creep" refers to:', options: ['A project finishing early', 'Uncontrolled changes or continuous growth in a project\'s scope', 'A team member leaving', 'Reducing the budget'], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: 'Scope creep happens when new features are added without adjusting time or cost.' },
                    { id: 18, text: 'Which of these is a crucial "Soft Skill" for a Project Manager?', options: ['Advanced coding', 'Effective Communication', 'Operating heavy machinery', 'Complex calculus'], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: 'PMs spend up to 90% of their time communicating with stakeholders and team members.' },
                    { id: 19, text: 'A "Deliverable" in project management is:', options: ['A tangible or intangible good/service produced as a result of the project', 'A delivery truck', 'A project delay', 'A cost estimate'], correctAnswer: 0, explanation: 'Deliverables are the actual outputs (like a software module or a physical report).' },
                    { id: 20, text: 'What is the main difference between Projects and Operations?', options: ['Operations are temporary, Projects are ongoing', 'Projects are temporary and unique, Operations are ongoing and repetitive', 'They are exactly the same', 'Operations cost more money'], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: 'Operations sustain the business daily, while projects drive change and uniqueness.' }
